ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A findings domain that contains physiological and morphological findings related to the respiratory system, including the organs that are involved in breathing such as the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi and lungs.

Concepts.definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to the respiratory system.

ValueDomain.preferredName: CDISC SDTM Respiratory Test Name Terminology Name
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: Terminology associated with the respiratory test name codelist of the Clinical Data Interchange Standards Consortium (CDISC) Study Data Tabulation Model (SDTM)._The words or language units by which a thing is known.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fastest flow rate of gas noted during the inspiratory cycle.

Concepts.definition: The fastest flow rate of gas noted during the inspiratory cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The time from the start of the test until the subject reaches his maximum expiratory gas flow rate.

Concepts.definition: The time from the start of the test until the subject reaches his maximum expiratory gas flow rate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum rate of gas flow, beginning at the point of peak inspiratory capacity, that can be sustained during forced exhalation for a defined period of time. This test is most often used in combination with other studies of lung function to diagnose and monitor obstructive and restrictive lung disease(s).

Concepts.definition: The maximum rate of gas flow, beginning at the point of peak inspiratory capacity, that can be sustained during forced exhalation for a defined period of time. This test is most often used in combination with other studies of lung function to diagnose and monitor obstructive and restrictive lung disease(s).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum rate of air flow expelled through the mouth, endotracheal, or tracheostomy tube during a cough.

Concepts.definition: The maximum rate of air flow expelled through the mouth, endotracheal, or tracheostomy tube during a cough.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of oxygen consumed by the body per heartbeat while at rest.

Concepts.definition: The volume of oxygen consumed by the body per heartbeat while at rest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The rate at which oxygen is absorbed and utilized by any given tissue in the body.

Concepts.definition: The rate at which oxygen is absorbed and utilized by any given tissue in the body.

PermissibleValues.value: Mean Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Mean Carbon Monoxide Diffusing Capability Test

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Mean Carbon Monoxide Diffusing Capability Test
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mean volume of the carbon monoxide that is transferred from inspired gas into the pulmonary capillary blood.

Concepts.longName: Mean Carbon Monoxide Diffusing Capability Test
Concepts.definition: The mean volume of the carbon monoxide that is transferred from inspired gas into the pulmonary capillary blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Forced inspiratory flow for a portion of the FVC curve at the point where the maximum portion of FVC is already inhaled. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: Forced inspiratory flow for a portion of the FVC curve at the point where the maximum portion of FVC is already inhaled. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated during inhalation against a fully occluded airway, which is used to measure the strength of respiratory muscles.

Concepts.definition: The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated during inhalation against a fully occluded airway, which is used to measure the strength of respiratory muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated by exhaling against a mouthpiece, which is a measure of the strength of respiratory muscles.

Concepts.definition: The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated by exhaling against a mouthpiece, which is a measure of the strength of respiratory muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of gas in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to eliminate the tracer to the pre-defined endpoint. Practically, this is the point where the end tidal concentration of inert gas is less than 1/40th of the opening concentration.

Concepts.definition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of gas in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to eliminate the tracer to the pre-defined endpoint. Practically, this is the point where the end tidal concentration of inert gas is less than 1/40th of the opening concentration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of gas an individual can inhale from the point of maximal exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of gas an individual can inhale from the point of maximal exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal exhalation (IRV plus TV).

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal exhalation (IRV plus TV).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The measure of the force of the column of air in the conducting airways.

Concepts.definition: The measure of the force of the column of air in the conducting airways.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The change in IC following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment IC value. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: The change in IC following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment IC value. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The diffusion capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide adjusted for the ratio of hemoglobin concentration to alveolar volume.

Concepts.longName: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio
Concepts.definition: The diffusion capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide adjusted for the ratio of hemoglobin concentration to alveolar volume.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An assessment of the diffusion capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.

Concepts.longName: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide
Concepts.definition: An assessment of the diffusion capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of air remaining in the lungs after a normal exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The volume of air remaining in the lungs after a normal exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of gas a subject can forcefully exhale during the first six seconds following maximum inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The volume of gas a subject can forcefully exhale during the first six seconds following maximum inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after forced maximum inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after forced maximum inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of air that a subject can breathe in during the first second of inhalation after maximum exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The volume of air that a subject can breathe in during the first second of inhalation after maximum exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The difference in lung volume between maximal expiration to residual volume followed immediately by full inspiration to total lung capacity during forceful inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The difference in lung volume between maximal expiration to residual volume followed immediately by full inspiration to total lung capacity during forceful inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 75 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

Concepts.definition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 75 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 50 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

Concepts.definition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 50 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 25 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

Concepts.definition: The forced inspiratory flow rate at the point on the inspiratory flow-volume curve where 25 percent of the total volume of gas has been inhaled.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A calculated value based on all factors that influence the flow of gas from the airway opening to the alveoli, including airway resistance, and tissue resistance of the lung and chest wall.

Concepts.definition: A calculated value based on all factors that influence the flow of gas from the airway opening to the alveoli, including airway resistance, and tissue resistance of the lung and chest wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The energy dissipated relative to the elastic energy stored in the tissue in a P-V cycle. Fredberg, J.J., Stamenovic, D. (1 December 1989). On the Imperfect Elasticity of Lung Tissue. Journal of Applied Physiology, Vol. 67. Retrieved from https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/560/10/

Concepts.definition: The energy dissipated relative to the elastic energy stored in the tissue in a P-V cycle. Fredberg, J.J., Stamenovic, D. (1 December 1989). On the Imperfect Elasticity of Lung Tissue. Journal of Applied Physiology, Vol. 67. Retrieved from https://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/560/10/

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A reflection of energy conservation within a given tissue.

Concepts.definition: A reflection of energy conservation within a given tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of air moved into and out of the lungs during breathing at rest.

Concepts.definition: The volume of air moved into and out of the lungs during breathing at rest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The absolute volume of gas contained in the thoracic cavity at any given point in time and at any level of alveolar pressure.

Concepts.definition: The absolute volume of gas contained in the thoracic cavity at any given point in time and at any level of alveolar pressure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC).

Concepts.definition: A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement of the airway conductance relative to lung volume.

Concepts.definition: A measurement of the airway conductance relative to lung volume.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after slow maximum inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after slow maximum inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The reflection of the curvature of the upper portion of the deflationary limb of the pressure-volume curve.

Concepts.definition: The reflection of the curvature of the upper portion of the deflationary limb of the pressure-volume curve.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The difference between the volume at total lung capacity and the hypothesized volume at a transpulmonary pressure of zero.

Concepts.definition: The difference between the volume at total lung capacity and the hypothesized volume at a transpulmonary pressure of zero.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A representation of the exponential function described by the Salazar-Knowles equation, and an estimation of a subject's inspiratory capacity.

Concepts.definition: A representation of the exponential function described by the Salazar-Knowles equation, and an estimation of a subject's inspiratory capacity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The ratio of the amount of carbon dioxide produced to the amount of oxygen consumed in one breath. This ratio is used to estimate the respiratory quotient, which indicates what type of fuel source the body is metabolising to provide energy.

Concepts.definition: The ratio of the amount of carbon dioxide produced to the amount of oxygen consumed in one breath. This ratio is used to estimate the respiratory quotient, which indicates what type of fuel source the body is metabolising to provide energy.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of air remaining in the lungs after a maximal exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The volume of air remaining in the lungs after a maximal exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The static elastic recoil pressure of the lungs at a given lung volume.

Concepts.definition: The static elastic recoil pressure of the lungs at a given lung volume.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The measurement of the ability of the lung to store energy, which is required for passive expiration. Reactance consists of two components: the negative component reflects capacitive behavior (C) and corresponds to both the thoraco-pulmonary elasticity and to changes in the available lung volumes in the distal compartments of the lung; the positive component of reactance has inertial characteristics (I) describing the moving air column in the bronchial tree.

Concepts.definition: The measurement of the ability of the lung to store energy, which is required for passive expiration. Reactance consists of two components: the negative component reflects capacitive behavior (C) and corresponds to both the thoraco-pulmonary elasticity and to changes in the available lung volumes in the distal compartments of the lung; the positive component of reactance has inertial characteristics (I) describing the moving air column in the bronchial tree.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of gas an individual can inhale from the point of maximal exhalation expressed as a percentage of the expected result value for healthy individuals of similar age, sex, height, and race.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of gas an individual can inhale from the point of maximal exhalation expressed as a percentage of the expected result value for healthy individuals of similar age, sex, height, and race.

PermissibleValues.value: Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement of carbon monoxide (CO) transfer from inspired gas to pulmonary capillary blood. During the test, the subject inspires a gas containing CO and one or more tracer gases to allow determination of the gas exchanging capability of the lungs.

Concepts.definition: A measurement of carbon monoxide (CO) transfer from inspired gas to pulmonary capillary blood. During the test, the subject inspires a gas containing CO and one or more tracer gases to allow determination of the gas exchanging capability of the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The quantity of fresh gas that enters the alveoli during inspiration.

Concepts.definition: The quantity of fresh gas that enters the alveoli during inspiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An assessment of the opposition to airflow through the respiratory tract on inspiration and/or expiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The instantaneous rate of gas flow in the airway, expressed as the pressure difference between any given part of the airway and the alveoli; it is the reciprocal of airway resistance (Raw).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A test of lung function, the FEV6 is the volume exhaled during six seconds of a forced expiratory maneuver started from the level of total lung capacity.

Concepts.definition: A test of lung function, the FEV6 is the volume exhaled during six seconds of a forced expiratory maneuver started from the level of total lung capacity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume exhaled during the first three seconds of a forced expiratory maneuver that is started from the level of total lung capacity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A test of lung function, the FEV1 is the volume exhaled during the first second of a forced expiratory maneuver started from the level of total lung capacity. It is the most frequently used index for assessing bronchoconstriction or bronchodilatation. (from http://www.spirxpert.com/indices7.htm)

Concepts.definition: A test of lung function, the FEV1 is the volume exhaled during the first second of a forced expiratory maneuver started from the level of total lung capacity. It is the most frequently used index for assessing bronchoconstriction or bronchodilatation.

Concepts.longName: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Flow at 25-75 Percent
Concepts.definition: The mean forced expiratory flow rate at 25-75% of the forced vital capacity as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can exhale from the lungs after a tidal exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air a subject can exhale from the lungs after a tidal exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The calculated ratio of the lung's alveolar volume with respect to its diffusion capacity for carbon monoxide, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.longName: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio
Concepts.definition: The calculated ratio of the lung's alveolar volume with respect to its diffusion capacity for carbon monoxide, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The degree to which inhaled carbon monoxide diffuses from the alveoli into the blood, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.longName: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide
Concepts.definition: The degree to which inhaled carbon monoxide diffuses from the alveoli into the blood, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The change in PEF following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment PEF value. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: The change in PEF following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment PEF value. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximal flow achieved during the maximally forced inspiration through the nose initiated at maximum exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The maximal flow achieved during the maximally forced inspiration through the nose initiated at maximum exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The amount of three dimensional space occupied by the effusion fluid.

Concepts.definition: The amount of three dimensional space occupied by the effusion fluid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indication as to whether a malignancy is present.

Concepts.definition: An indication as to whether a malignancy is present.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indication as to whether effusion is present.

Concepts.definition: An indication as to whether effusion is present.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A description of the basis for the determination that a malignancy is present.

Concepts.definition: A description of the basis for the determination that a malignancy is present.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indication as to whether pneumonia has occurred.

Concepts.definition: An indication as to whether pneumonia has occurred.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indication as to whether infiltrates have occurred.

Concepts.definition: An indication as to whether infiltrates have occurred.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An act or process of elucidation, explication, or explanation of the meaning of an event or thing.

Concepts.definition: An act or process of elucidation, explication, or explanation of the meaning of an event or thing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of gas in a specified airway or set of airways at a specified point in time in the respiratory cycle.

Concepts.definition: The total volume of gas in a specified airway or set of airways at a specified point in time in the respiratory cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A parameter used in functional respiratory imaging, derived by dividing the airway volume of a specified intrapulmonary region by the total volume of the same specified intrapulmonary region.

Concepts.definition: A parameter used in functional respiratory imaging, derived by dividing the airway volume of a specified intrapulmonary region by the total volume of the same specified intrapulmonary region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An assessment of the size difference in comparison to a baseline or previous value.

Concepts.definition: An assessment of the size difference in comparison to a baseline or previous value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A parameter used in functional respiratory imaging, derived by dividing the airway volume of a specified intrapulmonary region by the total volume of the same specified intrapulmonary region, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: A parameter used in functional respiratory imaging, derived by dividing the airway volume of a specified intrapulmonary region by the total volume of the same specified intrapulmonary region, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC), as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC), as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Forced expiratory volume in three seconds as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.longName: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds
Concepts.definition: Forced expiratory volume in three seconds as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of gas in a specified airway or set of airways at a specified point in time in the respiratory cycle, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: The total volume of gas in a specified airway or set of airways at a specified point in time in the respiratory cycle, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement of respiratory tract resistance to airflow during inspiration and expiration, as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: A measurement of respiratory tract resistance to airflow during inspiration and expiration, as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds to Forced Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds to Forced Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the forced expiratory volume during the first three seconds of exhalation to the largest observed expired volume during a forced vital capacity maneuver.

Concepts.longName: Forced Expiratory Volume in 3 Seconds to Forced Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement
Concepts.definition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the forced expiratory volume during the first three seconds of exhalation to the largest observed expired volume during a forced vital capacity maneuver.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Slow Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Slow Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the forced expiratory volume during the first second of exhalation to the largest observed expired volume during a slow vital capacity maneuver.

Concepts.longName: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Slow Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement
Concepts.definition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the forced expiratory volume during the first second of exhalation to the largest observed expired volume during a slow vital capacity maneuver.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The amount of time required to reach a specific tidal volume as measured from the start of exhalation.

Concepts.definition: The amount of time required to reach a specific tidal volume as measured from the start of exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of the entirety of the airway tissue in a specified intrapulmonary region.

Concepts.definition: The volume of the entirety of the airway tissue in a specified intrapulmonary region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement of the gas retention in a specified intrapulmonary space at the end of exhalation.

Concepts.definition: A measurement of the gas retention in a specified intrapulmonary space at the end of exhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A test to evaluate amount of oxygen taken up by arterial blood and expressed as a fraction of total oxygen of inspired air. This test may include other test such as pulse oximetry for the measurement of arterial blood oxygen levels.

Concepts.definition: The molar fraction of oxygen in an inhaled gas.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Partial Pressure Arterial Oxygen to Fraction Inspired Oxygen Ratio Measurement

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Partial Pressure Arterial Oxygen to Fraction Inspired Oxygen Ratio Measurement
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The determination of the ratio of the pressure of oxygen dissolved in arterial blood to the percentage oxygen of an inhaled mixture of gasses in a biological specimen.

Concepts.longName: Partial Pressure Arterial Oxygen to Fraction Inspired Oxygen Ratio Measurement
Concepts.definition: The determination of the ratio of the pressure of oxygen dissolved in arterial blood to the percentage oxygen of an inhaled mixture of gasses in a biological specimen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The predicted maximum rate of oxygen uptake that is derived from physiological responses to submaximal exercise performance and is used as a measure of cardiorespiratory fitness.

Concepts.definition: The predicted maximum rate of oxygen uptake that is derived from physiological responses to submaximal exercise performance and is used as a measure of cardiorespiratory fitness.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of air that can be forcibly exhaled during the first 3/4 second following maximal inhalation.

Concepts.definition: The volume of air that can be forcibly exhaled during the first 3/4 second following maximal inhalation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of gas in a lobe of the lung at a specified point in time during the respiratory cycle, as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: The total volume of gas in a lobe of the lung at a specified point in time during the respiratory cycle, as a proportion of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the oxygen-hemoglobin saturation of a volume of blood to the volumetric fraction of oxygen in the inhaled gas.

Concepts.definition: A relative measurement (ratio or percentage) of the oxygen-hemoglobin saturation of a volume of blood to the volumetric fraction of oxygen in the inhaled gas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The total volume of gas in a lobe of the lung at a specified point in time during the respiratory cycle.

Concepts.definition: The total volume of gas in a lobe of the lung at a specified point in time during the respiratory cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The point at which oxygen uptake no longer increases and beyond which no level of effort can raise it.

Concepts.definition: The point at which oxygen uptake no longer increases and beyond which no level of effort can raise it.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The volume of blood per unit time passing through a specified location, such as a point in a blood vessel or an entire organ. Units are ml/sec.

Concepts.definition: The volume of blood per unit time passing through a specified location, such as a point in a blood vessel or an entire organ. Units are ml/sec.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A subjective assessment of the primary lung abnormality pattern, generally based on size, distribution, and/or amount.

Concepts.definition: A subjective assessment of the primary lung abnormality pattern, generally based on size, distribution, and/or amount.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A subjective assessment of the distribution of the primary lung abnormality pattern.

Concepts.definition: A subjective assessment of the distribution of the primary lung abnormality pattern.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A determination of additional abnormalities and/or other observations that may be associated with the disease of interest, for which a targeted test has not been identified in the data.

Concepts.definition: A determination of additional abnormalities and/or other observations that may be associated with the disease of interest, for which a targeted test has not been identified in the data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A measurement of the efficiency of oxygen exchange by the lungs, which is calculated by multiplying the fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2) (in %) to mean airway pressure (Mpaw) and dividing by pressure of arterial oxygen (PaO2).

Concepts.definition: A measurement of the efficiency of oxygen exchange by the lungs, which is calculated by multiplying the fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2) (in %) to mean airway pressure (Mpaw) and dividing by pressure of arterial oxygen (PaO2).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An observation, assessment or examination of the respiratory system.

Concepts.definition: An observation, assessment or examination of the respiratory system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum volume of air an individual can exhale from the point of maximal inhalation as a percentage of the predicted normal value.

Concepts.definition: The maximum volume of air an individual can exhale from the point of maximal inhalation as a percentage of the predicted normal value.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The time taken to fully expirate air from the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The time taken to fully expirate air from the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Lung Clearance Index to 5% Initial Concentration
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of air in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to decrease the tracer to 5% (or 1/20th) of its initial concentration.

Concepts.longName: Lung Clearance Index to 5% Initial Concentration
Concepts.definition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of air in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to decrease the tracer to 5% (or 1/20th) of its initial concentration.

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Lung Clearance Index to 2.5% Initial Concentration
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of air in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to decrease the tracer to 2.5% (or 1/40th) of its initial concentration.

Concepts.longName: Lung Clearance Index to 2.5% Initial Concentration
Concepts.definition: A representative measurement of the number of times the volume of air in the lung at the start of the washout (the Functional Residual Capacity) must be recycled to decrease the tracer to 2.5% (or 1/40th) of its initial concentration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The point during activity or exercise at which ventilation begins to increase at a faster rate than oxygen consumption. This threshold is characterized by aerobic metabolism.

Concepts.definition: The point during activity or exercise at which ventilation begins to increase at a faster rate than oxygen consumption. This threshold is characterized by aerobic metabolism.
